[src:elysia-bun/javascript-engine] The first JavaScript engines were interpreters of the source code, but modern engines use just-in-time compilation to improve performance.
[src:elysia-bun/javascript-engine] JavaScript engines are typically developed by web browser vendors, and every major browser includes one.
[src:elysia-bun/javascript-engine] In a browser, the JavaScript engine runs in concert with the rendering engine via the Document Object Model and Web IDL bindings.
[src:elysia-bun/javascript-engine] However, the use of JavaScript engines is not limited to browsers; For example, the V8 engine is a core component of the Node.js runtime system.
[src:elysia-bun/javascript-engine] They are also called ECMAScript engines, after the official name of the specification.
[src:elysia-bun/javascript-engine] With the advent of WebAssembly, some engines can also execute this code in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:elysia-bun/javascript-engine] The first JavaScript engine was created by Brendan Eich in 1995 for the Netscape Navigator web browser.
[src:elysia-bun/javascript-engine] It was a rudimentary interpreter for the nascent language Eich invented.
[src:elysia-bun/javascript-engine] Google debuted its Chrome browser in 2008, introducing the V8 JavaScript engine that was at the time much faster than its competition.
[src:elysia-bun/javascript-engine] This sparked a race between browser vendors to deliver ever-faster JavaScript engines.
[src:elysia-bun/javascript-engine] The key innovations around this era were switching from basic tree-walking interpreters to stack- and register-based bytecode VM interpreters, just-in-time compilation (JIT), inline caching (hidden classes) and generational GC.
[src:elysia-bun/javascript-engine] Apple released the JIT-enabled Nitro engine in June 2008 for its Safari browser, which had 30% better performance than its predecessor.
[src:elysia-bun/javascript-engine] Mozilla followed suit in August 2008 with TraceMonkey, the first JIT compiler for SpiderMonkey engine, released in Firefox 3.1.
[src:elysia-bun/javascript-engine] Opera joined the performance race with their register-bytecode based and JIT-enabled Carakan engine, 2009 and released in April 2010.
[src:elysia-bun/javascript-engine] Microsoft's first JIT-enabled Chakra engine, in development since 2008, debuted as part of Internet Explorer 9 in 2011.
[src:elysia-bun/javascript-engine] Its major rewrite appeared in Microsoft Edge Legacy in 2015 and open-sourced as ChakraCore in 2016.
[src:elysia-bun/javascript-engine] Further performance gains in major JavaScript engines were later achieved with the introduction of multi-tiered JIT architectures.
[src:elysia-bun/javascript-engine] Progressively advanced JIT compilers are used to optimize hotspots in user code, with each next tier delivering ever more performant native code at the cost of slower compile time.
[src:elysia-bun/javascript-engine] Chrome was the first to implement it in V8 in 2010 with the introduction of Crankshaft, a 2-tiered JIT compiler.
[src:elysia-bun/javascript-engine] By 2023, architecture of V8 evolved into 4 tiers: Ignition – register-based bytecode interpreter, Sparkplug – a fast non-optimizing JIT compiler, Maglev and TurboFan – slower optimizing JIT compilers.
[src:elysia-bun/javascript-engine] JavaScriptCore today has a similar 4-tier architecture, while Firefox's SpiderMonkey and ChakraCore have 3 tiers (interpreter and 2-tiered JIT).
[src:elysia-bun/javascript-engine] V8's influence expanded beyond browsers with the release of Node.js in 2009 and its package manager npm in 2010.
[src:elysia-bun/javascript-engine] As their popularity exploded, V8 also became the engine powering vast amounts of server-side JavaScript code.
[src:elysia-bun/javascript-engine] In 2013, Electron framework appeared that let developers create desktop apps with web technologies as well, using Chromium with V8 and Node.js under the hood.
[src:elysia-bun/javascript-engine] Eventually asm.js and NaCl (a competing Google's technology) evolved into WebAssembly standard in 2017, with all major engines adding support for it.
[src:elysia-bun/javascript-engine] The six-year gap between ECMAScript 5 (2009) and ES6 (2015) marked a major inflection point for JavaScript engine development.
[src:elysia-bun/javascript-engine] Whereas ES5 was a relatively compact language with straightforward basic implementation, ES6 introduced foundations of modern JavaScript, with substantially increased complexity, as well as an annual release cycle for new specification versions.
[src:elysia-bun/javascript-engine] This put the focus not only on performance optimization, but also on keeping pace with the rapidly evolving standards (of both ECMAScript and wider web ecosystem) and led to a consolidation around engines that had the resources to do it.
[src:elysia-bun/javascript-engine] Many smaller projects did not end up fully implementing ES6 spec, and Opera and Microsoft both ceased developing their engines and adopted V8 in 2013 and 2021.
[src:elysia-bun/javascript-engine] Nashorn engine was dropped from OpenJDK over a similar concern about ECMAScript's rapid development.
[src:elysia-bun/javascript-engine] These engines have been discontinued and are mostly interesting for the historical perspective.
[src:elysia-bun/javascript-engine] Some may still be in use today for legacy purposes (especially Microsoft's old engines that continue to ship with Windows).
[src:elysia-bun/openapi-specification] The **OpenAPI Specification** (**OAS**), previously known as the **Swagger Specification**, is a specification for a machine-readable interface definition language for describing, producing, consuming and visualizing web services.
[src:elysia-bun/openapi-specification] Originally developed to support the Swagger framework, it became a separate project in 2015, overseen by the OpenAPI Initiative, an open-source collaboration project of the Linux Foundation.
[src:elysia-bun/openapi-specification] An OpenAPI Description (OAD) represents a formal description of an API that tools can use to generate code, documentation, test cases, and more.
[src:elysia-bun/openapi-specification] Swagger development began in early 2010 by Tony Tam, who was working at online dictionary company Wordnik.
[src:elysia-bun/openapi-specification] In March 2015, SmartBear Software acquired the open-source Swagger API specification from Reverb Technologies, Wordnik's parent company.
[src:elysia-bun/openapi-specification] In November 2015, SmartBear announced that it was donating the Swagger specification to a new organization called the OpenAPI Initiative, under the sponsorship of the Linux Foundation.
[src:elysia-bun/openapi-specification] Other founding member companies included 3scale, Apigee, Capital One, Google, IBM, Intuit, Microsoft, PayPal, and Restlet.
[src:elysia-bun/openapi-specification] On 1 January 2016, the Swagger specification was renamed the OpenAPI Specification (OAS) and was moved to a new GitHub repository.
[src:elysia-bun/openapi-specification] Two somewhat similar technologies, MuleSoft's RESTful API Modeling Language (RAML) and Apiary's API Blueprint, had been developed around the same time as what was then still called the Swagger Specification.
[src:elysia-bun/openapi-specification] The producers of both formats later joined the OpenAPI Initiative: Apiary in 2016 and MuleSoft in 2017.
[src:elysia-bun/openapi-specification] In July 2017, the OpenAPI Initiative released version 3.0.0 of its specification.
[src:elysia-bun/openapi-specification] In February 2021, the OpenAPI Initiative released version 3.1.0.
[src:elysia-bun/openapi-specification] In September 2025, the OpenAPI Initiative released version 3.2.0 of the OAS.
[src:elysia-bun/openapi-specification] Notable features include structured tags, first-class streaming media type support, support for arbitrary HTTP methods, clearer example semantics for serializations, OAuth2 device flow and metadata enhancements, and clarified path templating and routing semantics.
[src:elysia-bun/openapi-specification] The OAS describes the format for OpenAPI Descriptions (OADs), which can be used by a variety of applications, libraries, and tools.
[src:elysia-bun/openapi-specification] Applications can use OADs to automatically generate documentation of methods, parameters and data models.
[src:elysia-bun/openapi-specification] This helps keep the documentation, client libraries and source code in sync.
[src:elysia-bun/openapi-specification] When an OAD is used to generate source code stubs for servers, the process is called scaffolding.
[src:elysia-bun/openapi-specification] The paradigm of agreeing on an API contract first and then programming business logic afterwards, in contrast to coding the program first and then writing a retrospective description of its behavior as the contract, is called contract-first development.
[src:elysia-bun/openapi-specification] Since the interface is determined before any code is written, downstream developers can mock the server behavior and start testing right away.
[src:elysia-bun/openapi-specification] In this sense, contract-first development is also a practice of shift-left testing.
[src:elysia-bun/openapi-specification] The OpenAPI Specification is language-agnostic.
[src:elysia-bun/openapi-specification] With OpenAPI's declarative resource specification, clients can understand and consume services without knowledge of server implementation or access to the server code.
[src:elysia-bun/openapi-specification] The OpenAPI Initiative sponsored APIStrat from 2017 to 2019, converting it into the API Specifications Confererence (ASC) from 2020 to 2022.
[src:elysia-bun/openapi-specification] Starting in 2023, the initiative has instead sponsored OpenAPI tracks at multiple conferences throughout the year.
[src:elysia-bun/type-signature] In computer science, a **type signature** or **type annotation** defines the inputs and outputs of a function, subroutine or method.
[src:elysia-bun/type-signature] A type signature includes the number, types, and order of the function's arguments.
[src:elysia-bun/type-signature] One important use of a type signature is for function overload resolution, where one particular definition of a function to be called is selected among many overloaded forms.
[src:elysia-bun/type-signature] In C and C++, the type signature is declared by what is commonly known as a function prototype.
[src:elysia-bun/type-signature] Notice that the type of the result can be regarded as everything past the first supplied argument.
[src:elysia-bun/type-signature] This is a consequence of currying, which is made possible by Haskell's support for first-class functions; this function requires two inputs where one argument is supplied and the function is "curried" to produce a function for the argument not supplied.
[src:elysia-bun/type-signature] Thus, calling `f x`, where `f :: a -> b -> c`, yields a new function `f2 :: b -> c` that can be called `f2 b` to produce `c`.
[src:elysia-bun/type-signature] The actual type specifications can consist of an actual type, such as `Integer`, or a general type variable that is used in parametric polymorphic functions, such as `a`, or `b`, or `anyType`.
[src:elysia-bun/type-signature] Since Haskell supports higher-order functions, functions can be passed as arguments.
[src:elysia-bun/type-signature] This function takes in a function with type signature `a -> a` and returns data of type `a` out.
[src:elysia-bun/type-signature] In the Java virtual machine, *internal type signatures* are used to identify methods and classes at the level of the virtual machine code.
[src:elysia-bun/type-signature] Example: The method `String String.substring(int, int)` is represented in bytecode as `Ljava/lang/String.substring(II)Ljava/lang/String;` .
[src:elysia-bun/type-signature] A function signature consists of the function prototype.
[src:elysia-bun/type-signature] It specifies the general information about a function like the name, scope and parameters.
[src:elysia-bun/type-signature] Many programming languages use name mangling in order to pass along more semantic information from the compilers to the linkers.
[src:elysia-bun/type-signature] In addition to mangling, there is an excess of information in a function signature (stored internally to most compilers) which is not readily available, but may be accessed.
[src:elysia-bun/type-signature] Understanding the notion of a function signature is an important concept for all computer science studies.
[src:elysia-bun/type-signature] The practice of multiple inheritance requires consideration of the function signatures to avoid unpredictable results.
[src:elysia-bun/type-signature] Computer science theory, and the concept of polymorphism in particular, make much use of the concept of function signature.
[src:elysia-bun/type-signature] In the C programming language, a signature is roughly equivalent to its prototype definition.
[src:elysia-bun/type-signature] In the ML family of programming languages, "signature" is used as a keyword referring to a construct of the module system that plays the role of an interface.
[src:elysia-bun/type-signature] In computer programming, especially object-oriented programming, a method is commonly identified by its unique **method signature**, which usually includes the method name and the number, types, and order of its parameters.
[src:elysia-bun/type-signature] A method signature is the smallest type of a method.
[src:elysia-bun/type-signature] In C, the method signature is the method name and the number and type of its parameters, but it is possible to have variadic parameters, but these are not type-safe.
[src:elysia-bun/type-signature] Manipulation of these parameters can be done by using the routines in the standard library header `<stdarg.h>`.
[src:elysia-bun/type-signature] In C++, in addition to the C-style function return type appearing before, the return type may also follow the parameter list, which is referred to as a trailing return type.
[src:elysia-bun/type-signature] The difference is only syntactic; in either case, the resulting signature is identical.
[src:elysia-bun/type-signature] Note `void doSomething(auto... args);` is equivalent to `template <typename...
[src:elysia-bun/type-signature] In Java, a method signature is composed of a name and the number, type, and order of its parameters.
[src:elysia-bun/type-signature] Return types and thrown exceptions are not considered to be a part of the method signature, nor are the names of parameters; they are ignored by the compiler for checking method uniqueness.
[src:elysia-bun/type-signature] The method signatures help distinguish overloaded methods (methods with the same name) in a class.
[src:elysia-bun/type-signature] Return types are not included in overloading.
[src:elysia-bun/type-signature] Only method signatures should be used to distinguish overloaded methods.
[src:elysia-bun/type-signature] Variadic parameters in Java are represented with ellipses on the final parameter.
[src:elysia-bun/type-signature] These behave identically to an array, but in the JVM bytecode the method is marked variadic.
[src:elysia-bun/type-signature] The types in the arguments are used for the multiple dispatch.
[src:elysia-bun/type-signature] The return type is validated when the function returns a value, and a runtime exception is raised if the type of the value does not agree with the specified type.
[src:elysia-bun/type-signature] Abstract types are allowed and are encouraged for implementing general behavior that is common to all subtypes.
[src:elysia-bun/type-signature] The above function can therefore be rewritten as follows.
[src:elysia-bun/type-signature] In this case, the function can accept any Integer and Real subtypes accordingly.
[src:elysia-bun/type-signature] Types are completely optional in function arguments.
[src:elysia-bun/type-signature] When unspecified, it is equivalent to using the type Any, which is the super-type of all types.
[src:elysia-bun/type-signature] It is idiomatic to specify argument types but not return type.
[src:elysia-bun/type-signature] In the Objective-C programming language, method signatures for an object are declared in the interface header file.
[src:elysia-bun/type-signature] defines a method `initWithInt` that returns a general object (an `id`) and takes one integer argument.
[src:elysia-bun/typescript] TypeScript may be used to develop JavaScript applications for both client-side and server-side execution (as with React.js, Node.js, Deno or Bun).
[src:elysia-bun/typescript] Multiple options are available for transpiling.
[src:elysia-bun/typescript] The default TypeScript Compiler can be used, or the Babel compiler can be invoked to convert TypeScript to JavaScript.
[src:elysia-bun/typescript] TypeScript supports definition files that can contain type information of existing JavaScript libraries, much like C++ header files can describe the structure of existing object files.
[src:elysia-bun/typescript] This enables other programs to use the values defined in the files as if they were statically typed TypeScript entities.
[src:elysia-bun/typescript] There are third-party header files for popular libraries such as jQuery, MongoDB, and D3.js.
[src:elysia-bun/typescript] TypeScript headers for the Node.js library modules are also available, allowing development of Node.js programs within TypeScript.
[src:elysia-bun/typescript] The TypeScript compiler is written in TypeScript and compiled to JavaScript.
[src:elysia-bun/typescript] It is licensed under the Apache License 2.0.
[src:elysia-bun/typescript] Anders Hejlsberg, lead architect of C# and creator of Delphi and Turbo Pascal, has worked on developing TypeScript.
[src:elysia-bun/typescript] TypeScript was released to the public in October 2012, with version 0.8, after two years of internal development at Microsoft.
[src:elysia-bun/typescript] Soon after the initial public release, Miguel de Icaza praised the language, but criticized the lack of mature integrated development environment (IDE) support apart from Microsoft Visual Studio, which was unavailable then on Linux and macOS.
[src:elysia-bun/typescript] As of April 2021 there is support in other IDEs and text editors, including Emacs, Vim, WebStorm, Atom and Microsoft's own Visual Studio Code.
[src:elysia-bun/typescript] TypeScript 0.9, released in 2013, added support for generics.
[src:elysia-bun/typescript] TypeScript 1.0 was released at Microsoft's Build developer conference in 2014.
[src:elysia-bun/typescript] Visual Studio 2013 Update 2 provided built-in support for TypeScript.
[src:elysia-bun/typescript] Further improvement were made in July 2014, when the development team announced a new TypeScript compiler, asserted to have a five-fold performance increase.
[src:elysia-bun/typescript] Simultaneously, the source code, which was initially hosted on CodePlex, was moved to GitHub.
[src:elysia-bun/typescript] On 22 September 2016, TypeScript 2.0 was released, introducing several features, including the ability for programmers to optionally enforce null safety.
[src:elysia-bun/typescript] TypeScript 3.0 was released on 30 July 2018, bringing many language additions like tuples in rest parameters and spread expressions, rest parameters with tuple types, generic rest parameters and so on.
[src:elysia-bun/typescript] TypeScript 4.0 was released on 20 August 2020.
[src:elysia-bun/typescript] While 4.0 did not introduce any breaking changes, it added language features such as Custom JSX Factories and Variadic Tuple Types.
[src:elysia-bun/typescript] TypeScript 5.0 was released on 16 March 2023 and included support for decorators.
[src:elysia-bun/typescript] On March 11, 2025, Anders Hejlsberg announced on the TypeScript blog that the team is working on a Go port of the TypeScript compiler to be released as TypeScript version 7.0 later this year.
[src:elysia-bun/typescript] It is expected to feature a 10x speedup.
[src:elysia-bun/typescript] On December 2nd, 2025, Daniel Rosenwasser announced on the blog that TypeScript 6.0 will be the last release written in TypeScript itself, and TypeScript 7.0 will be the first Go-based release.
[src:elysia-bun/typescript] TypeScript originated from the shortcomings of JavaScript for developing large-scale applications both at Microsoft and among their external customers.
[src:elysia-bun/typescript] Challenges with dealing with complex JavaScript code led to demand for custom tooling to ease developing of components in the language.
[src:elysia-bun/typescript] Developers sought a solution that would not break compatibility with the ECMAScript (ES) standard and its ecosystem, so a compiler was developed to transform a superset of JavaScript with type annotations and classes (TypeScript files) back into vanilla ECMAScript 5 code.
[src:elysia-bun/typescript] TypeScript classes were based on the then-proposed ECMAScript 6 class specification to make writing prototypal inheritance less verbose and error-prone, and type annotations enabled IntelliSense and improved tooling.
[src:elysia-bun/typescript] Syntactically, TypeScript is very similar to JScript .NET, another Microsoft implementation of the ECMA-262 language standard that added support for static typing and classical object-oriented language features such as classes, inheritance, interfaces, and namespaces.
[src:elysia-bun/typescript] As TypeScript is simply a superset of JavaScript, existing JavaScript can be adapted to TypeScript and TypeScript program can seamlessly consume JavaScript.
[src:elysia-bun/typescript] The compiler can target all ECMAScript versions 5 and above, transpiling modern features like classes and arrow functions to their older counterparts.
[src:elysia-bun/typescript] With TypeScript, it is possible to use existing JavaScript code, incorporate popular JavaScript libraries, and call TypeScript-generated code from other JavaScript.
[src:elysia-bun/typescript] Type declarations for these libraries are usually provided with the source code but can be declared or installed separately if needed.
[src:elysia-bun/typescript] The TypeScript compiler, named `tsc`, is written in TypeScript.
[src:elysia-bun/typescript] As a result, it can be compiled into regular JavaScript and can then be executed in any JavaScript engine (e.g. a browser).
[src:elysia-bun/typescript] The compiler package comes bundled with a script host that can execute the compiler.
[src:elysia-bun/typescript] It is also available as a Node.js package that uses Node.js as a host.
[src:elysia-bun/typescript] The compiler is currently being rewritten in Go for version 7.
[src:elysia-bun/typescript] The compiler can *target* a given edition of ECMAScript (such as ECMAScript 5 for legacy browser compatibility), but by default compiles for the latest standards.
[src:elysia-bun/typescript] Using plug-ins, TypeScript can be integrated with build automation tools, including Grunt (grunt-ts), Apache Maven (TypeScript Maven Plugin), Gulp (gulp-typescript) and Gradle (TypeScript Gradle Plugin).
[src:elysia-bun/typescript] TSLint scans TypeScript code for conformance to a set of standards and guidelines.
[src:elysia-bun/typescript] ESLint, a standard JavaScript linter, also provided some support for TypeScript via community plugins.
[src:elysia-bun/typescript] However, ESLint's inability to leverage TypeScript's language services precluded certain forms of semantic linting and program-wide analysis.
[src:elysia-bun/typescript] In early 2019, the TSLint team announced the linter's deprecation in favor of `typescript-eslint`, a joint effort of the TSLint, ESLint and TypeScript teams to consolidate linting under the ESLint umbrella for improved performance, community unity and developer accessibility.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] A **web framework** (**WF**), **web application framework** (**WAF**), or **web development framework** is a software framework that is designed to support the development of web applications including web services, web resources, and web APIs.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] Web frameworks provide a standard way to build and deploy web applications on the World Wide Web.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] Web frameworks aim to automate the overhead associated with common activities performed in web development.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] For example, many web frameworks provide libraries for database access, templating frameworks, and session management, and they often promote code reuse.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] Although they often target development of dynamic web sites, they are also applicable to static websites.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] As the design of the World Wide Web was not inherently dynamic, early hypertext consisted of hand-coded HTML text files that were published on web servers.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] Any modifications to published pages needed to be performed by the pages' author.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] In 1993, the Common Gateway Interface (CGI) standard was introduced for interfacing external applications with web servers, to provide a dynamic web page that reflected user inputs.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] Original implementations of the CGI interface typically had adverse effects on the server load however, because each request started a separate process.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] More recent implementations utilize persistent processes amongst other techniques to reduce the footprint in the server's resources and offer a general performance boost.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] In 1995, fully integrated server/language development environments first emerged and new web-specific languages were introduced, such as ColdFusion, PHP, and Active Server Pages.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] Although the vast majority of languages for creating dynamic web pages have libraries to help with common tasks, web applications often require specific libraries for particular tasks, such as creating HTML (for example, Jakarta Faces).
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] In the late 1990s, mature, "full stack" frameworks began to appear, that often gathered multiple libraries useful for web development into a single cohesive software stack for web developers to use.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] Most web frameworks are based on the model–view–controller (MVC) pattern.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] Many frameworks follow the MVC architectural pattern to separate the data model into business rules (the "controller") and the user interface (the "view").
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] This is generally considered a good practice as it modularizes code, promotes code reuse, and allows multiple interfaces to be applied.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] In web applications, this permits different views to be presented, for example serving different web pages for mobile vs. desktop browsers, or providing machine-readable web service interfaces.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] Most MVC frameworks follow a push-based architecture also called "action-based".
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] These frameworks use actions that do the required processing, and then "push" the data to the view layer to render the results.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] An alternative to this is pull-based architecture, sometimes also called "component-based".
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] These frameworks start with the view layer, which can then "pull" results from multiple controllers as needed.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] In this architecture, multiple controllers can be involved with a single view.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] In three-tier organization, applications are structured around three physical tiers: client, application, and database.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] The application contains the business logic, running on a server and communicates with the client using HTTP.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] The client on web applications is a web browser that runs HTML generated by the application layer.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] The term should not be confused with MVC, where, unlike in three-tier architecture, it is considered a good practice to keep business logic away from the controller, the "middle layer".
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] Web frameworks must function according to the architectural rules of browsers and protocols such as HTTP, which is stateless.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] Webpages are served up by a server and can then be modified by the browser using JavaScript.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] Either approach has its advantages and disadvantages.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] Server-side page changes typically require that the page be refreshed, but allow any language to be used and more computing power to be utilized.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] Client-side changes allow the page to be updated in small chunks which feels like a desktop application, but are limited to JavaScript and run in the user's browser, which may have limited computing power.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] Applications which make heavy use of JavaScript and only refresh parts of the page, are called single-page applications and typically make use of a client-side JavaScript web framework to organize the code.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] Examples include Backbone.js, AngularJS, Angular, Ember.js, ReactJS, jQuery UI, Svelte, and Vue.js.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] JavaScript-based web application frameworks, such as React and Vue, provide extensive capabilities but come with associated trade-offs.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] These frameworks often extend or enhance features available through native web technologies, such as routing, component-based development, and state management.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] Frameworks can introduce abstraction layers that may contribute to performance overhead, larger bundle sizes, and increased complexity.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] Modern frameworks, such as React 18 and Vue 3, address these challenges with features like concurrent rendering, tree-shaking, and selective hydration.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] While these advancements improve rendering efficiency and resource management, their benefits depend on the specific application and implementation context.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] Lightweight frameworks, such as Svelte and Preact, take different architectural approaches, with Svelte eliminating the virtual DOM entirely in favor of compiling components to efficient JavaScript code, and Preact offering a minimal, compatible alternative to React.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] Framework choice depends on an application’s requirements, including the team’s expertise, performance goals, and development priorities.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] A newer category of web frameworks, including enhance.dev, Astro, and Fresh, leverages native web standards while minimizing abstractions and development tooling.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] These solutions emphasize progressive enhancement, server-side rendering, and optimizing performance.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] Astro renders static HTML by default while hydrating only interactive parts.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] Fresh focuses on server-side rendering with zero runtime overhead.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] Enhance.dev prioritizes progressive enhancement patterns using Web Components.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] While these tools reduce reliance on client-side JavaScript by shifting logic to build-time or server-side execution, they still use JavaScript where necessary for interactivity.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] This approach makes them particularly suitable for performance-critical and content-focused applications.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] Frameworks typically set the control flow of a program and allow the user of the framework to "hook into" that flow by exposing various events.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] This "inversion of control" design pattern is considered to be a defining principle of a framework, and benefits the code by enforcing a common flow for a team which everyone can customize in similar ways.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] For example, some popular "microframeworks" such as Ruby's Sinatra (which inspired Express.js) allow for "middleware" hooks prior to and after HTTP requests.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] These middleware functions can be anything, and allow the user to define logging, authentication and session management, and redirecting.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] Web caching is the caching of web documents in order to reduce bandwidth usage, server load, and perceived "lag".
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] A web cache stores copies of documents passing through it; subsequent requests may be satisfied from the cache if certain conditions are met.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] Some application frameworks provide mechanisms for caching documents and bypassing various stages of the page's preparation, such as database access or template interpretation.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] Some web frameworks come with authentication and authorization frameworks, that enable the web server to identify the users of the application, and restrict access to functions based on some defined criteria.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] Drupal is one example that provides role-based access to pages, and provides a web-based interface for creating users and assigning them roles.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] Many web frameworks create a unified API to a database backend, enabling web applications to work with a variety of databases with no code changes, and allowing programmers to work with higher-level concepts.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] Additionally, some object-oriented frameworks contain mapping tools to provide object-relational mapping, which maps objects to tuples.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] Some frameworks minimize web application configuration through the use of introspection and/or following well-known conventions.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] For example, many Java frameworks use Hibernate as a persistence layer, which can generate a database schema at runtime capable of persisting the necessary information.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] This allows the application designer to design business objects without needing to explicitly define a database schema.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] Frameworks such as Ruby on Rails can also work in reverse, that is, define properties of model objects at runtime based on a database schema.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] Other features web frameworks may provide include transactional support and database migration tools.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] A framework's URL mapping or routing facility is the mechanism by which the framework interprets URLs.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] Some frameworks, such as Drupal and Django, match the provided URL against pre-determined patterns using regular expressions, while some others use rewriting techniques to translate the provided URL into one that the underlying engine will recognize.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] Another technique is that of graph traversal such as used by Zope, where a URL is decomposed in steps that traverse an object graph (of models and views).
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] A URL mapping system that uses pattern matching or rewriting to route and handle requests allows for shorter more "friendly URLs" to be used, increasing the simplicity of the site and allowing for better indexing by search engines.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] For example, a URL that ends with "/page.cgi?cat=science&topic=physics" could be changed to simply "/page/science/physics".
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] This makes the URL easier for people to remember, read and write, and provides search engines with better information about the structural layout of the site.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] A graph traversal approach also tends to result in the creation of friendly URLs.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] A shorter URL such as "/page/science" tends to exist by default as that is simply a shorter form of the longer traversal to "/page/science/physics".
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] Ajax, shorthand for "*Asynchronous JavaScript and XML*", is a web development technique for creating web applications.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] The intent is to make web pages feel more responsive by exchanging small amounts of data with the server behind the scenes, so that the entire web page does not have to be reloaded each time the user requests a change.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] This is intended to increase a web page's interactivity, speed, maintainability, and usability.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] Due to the complexity of Ajax programming in JavaScript, there are numerous Ajax frameworks that exclusively deal with Ajax support.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] Some Ajax frameworks are even embedded as a part of larger frameworks.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] For example, the jQuery JavaScript library is included in Ruby on Rails.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] With the increased interest in developing "Web 2.0" rich web applications, the complexity of programming directly in Ajax and JavaScript has become so apparent that compiler technology has stepped in, to allow developers to code in high-level languages such as Java, Python and Ruby.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] The first of these compilers was Morfik followed by Google Web Toolkit, with ports to Python and Ruby in the form of Pyjs and RubyJS following some time after.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] These compilers and their associated widget set libraries make the development of rich media Ajax applications much more akin to that of developing desktop applications.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] Some frameworks provide tools for creating and providing web services.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] These utilities may offer similar tools as the rest of the web application.
[src:elysia-bun/web-framework] A number of newer Web 2.0 RESTful frameworks are now providing resource-oriented architecture (ROA) infrastructure for building collections of resources in a sort of Semantic Web ontology, based on concepts from Resource Description Framework (RDF).
